div.div:
Trajectory planner generates a robot velocity from its current and target positions.
If open-loop, then a target motor position is sent without checking if the position has been reached.
If closed-loop, then a PID could be used to check the error between actual and target position.
Trajectory planner could be extrapolated to control current and target velocity, or current and target heading.
Simplest implementation would be to independently deal with rotation and linear movements.
I will define a primitive trajectory control system as planning/control of a purely straight-line or purely rotational velocity profile. This differs from a "composite" trajectory control system which will merge the two velocities into a single continuous movement.

div.div:
How to engineer a mechatronic system?
1. Implement an open-loop system.
2. Does the open-loop system achieve desirable results?
3. If not, design a closed-loop system.
4. What state do we want to control? What sensor do we need to monitor that state?
5. Is the sensor accurate? Does a filter need to be implemented? Does another sensor need to be fused?
6. What kind of closed-loop controller is suitable?

div.div:
This architectural diagram shows how the labs are relevant.
This is just one possible solution to developing a maze-solving robot. Filters, sensors, and control systems can be used anywhere and in any way possible - but this template is to help students have a high-level perspective to how to approach robot design.
The architecture covers every aspect that a learning MTRN student should know i.e. filtering, data fusion, control systems - but is minimal enough for students to just get a working robot. If students want to win the competition, then they need to extrapolate what they learnt and apply it on other subsystems.
It's up to students to figure out how to interface these subsystems together i.e. integrating the work done in the labs.

div.div:
Motor drive subsystem (assuming position control) transforms the target motor position into a PWM signal.
If the motor drive subsystem is open-loop, then how long the PWM is sent is hardcoded (this will be extremely unreliable).
If the motor drive subsystem is closed-loop, then a PID controller controls the PWM signal for us by checking how big the error is between the target position and the actual position.
